Task 2 System Configuration and Advanced System Settings

- System Configuration (MSConfig)
- Purpose: advanced troubleshooting, diagnosing startup issues.
Tabs:
- General: Normal, Diagnostic, or Selective startup.
- Boot: configure OS boot options.
- Services: lists all background services.
- Startup: on servers, startup items are managed via shell:startup.
- Tools: provides access to system utilities with descriptions and launch commands.
- Advanced System Settings
- Access via search: View advanced system settings.
- Performance Options:
- Page file acts as virtual memory when RAM is full.
- Settings show drive location, initial size, maximum size, and management options.
- Startup and Recovery:
- Configures crash dump files for system errors (BSOD).
- Dump types: Automatic, Kernel, Small (256 KB), Complete, None.

---

Task 3 Change UAC Settings

- UAC protects against unauthorized system changes.
- Settings adjustable via slider with four levels:
- Always notify: highest security, alerts for all changes, dims desktop.
- Notify for apps: default; alerts only when apps make changes.
- Notify without dimming: same as above, but desktop doesn’t dim.
- Never notify: disables UAC prompts (not recommended).

---

Task 4 Computer Management (compmgmt)

System Tools
- Task Scheduler: automate tasks/scripts.
- Event Viewer: audit trail of system activity.
- Shared Folders: view shares, sessions, open files.
- Local Users and Groups: manage accounts and permissions.
- Performance Monitor (perfmon): real-time or logged performance data.
- Device Manager: configure hardware devices.
- Storage
- Disk Management: advanced storage tasks (setup new drives, extend/shrink partitions, assign/change drive letters).
- Services and Applications
- Services: view and configure background services (Automatic, Manual, Disabled).
- WMI Control: manage Windows Management Instrumentation (PowerShell replaces WMIC).

---

Task 5 System Information (msinfo32)

- Displays system details for diagnostics.
- Sections: System Summary, Hardware Resources, Components, Software Environment.
- Environment Variables store OS data (e.g., %windir%).
- Search bar allows filtering (e.g., search for IP address).

---

Task 6 Resource Monitor (resmon)

- Displays CPU, memory, disk, and network usage per process.
- Useful for advanced troubleshooting and identifying deadlocks or file conflicts.
- Real-time graphical pane shows system activity visually.

---

## Task 7 Command Prompt (cmd)

- Legacy interface for interacting with the OS.
Basic Commands:
hostname: outputs computer name.
- whoami: outputs logged-in user.
- Troubleshooting Commands:
- ipconfig: shows network settings.
- ipconfig /?: displays help manual.
- cls: clears screen.
- netstat: shows protocol statistics and TCP/IP connections.
- net: manages network resources with sub-commands (user, localgroup, use, share, session).
- net help user: displays help for sub-commands.

---

## Task 8 Registry Editor (regedit)

- Windows Registry: hierarchical database storing system, user, application, and hardware configuration.
- Contains profiles, installed applications, folder/icon settings, hardware info, and port usage.
- Warning: modifying registry can disrupt system operations.
- Access via Registry Editor (regedit).

